  doi = {10.1016/0022-0981(83)90043-6},
  urldate = {2025-07-12},
  abstract = {Nerita scabricosta (Lamarck, 1822) and Nerita funiculata (Menke, 1851) are common, herbivorous snails which occur together on the Pacific rocky coast of Panama. We show that the foraging patterns of both species are constrained by 1.(1) the probability of predation by fishes,2.(2) overheating and desiccation. Their different responses to these factors control their effects on the rest of the intertidal community. Both species are found in a limited number of microhabitats while inactive. N. funiculata is restricted to mid-zone crevices. Individuals forage out from these crevices for short periods on ebbing or rising tides. Movement is limited to {$\approx$}50 cm on either side of occupied crevices. The rock within {$\approx$}10 cm from crevices containing N. funiculata is bare; crustose algal cover increases with distance from the crevice. There is no change in algal cover with distance around crevices which naturally lack N. funiculata and in experimental removals algal crusts settle or grow in to cover 80--100\% of the rock. Thus N. funiculata affects local, discrete areas of intertidal substratum by causing small-scale patchiness in algal cover. N. scabricosta is found at upper tidal levels while inactive during high tide, aggregated above the high-water mark in crevices or on vertical surfaces. Individuals move down and graze from the high to the low zones as the tide falls. They retreat to the high intertidal zone as the tide rises and once again become inactive until the tide falls. Thus, unlike its congener, N. scabricosta exerts grazing effects throughout the intertidal zone. We demonstrate that this snail affects 1.(1) barnacle settlement,2.(2) the density and size structure of co-occurring species of Littorina,3.(3) the abundance of crustose algae from the high to the low mid-zones. These differences in community effects between species appear to be related to the larger body size reached by N. scabricosta.},
